Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Qatar. The Qatar authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus.
From the evening of 16 March for a period of at least 14 days (which may be subject to further extension), no international passengers – including those with a residence permit - will be allowed to enter Qatar. Transit passengers travelling on to another destination will still be able to transfer through Qatar, and some flights continue to operate. You should check with your airline or travel company for the latest information if you are planning to leave Qatar. Flights are subject to change or cancellation at short notice.
You should contact your tour operator, transport or accommodation provider for information on the impact on any existing travel plans. If you need further information about entry requirements, or have queries around the extension of visas, contact the local immigration authorities or the nearest Qatar embassy. You should also check with your airline or travel company for the latest information.
Qatar’s Ministry of Public Health has published advice on how to limit the spread of coronavirus and have introduced a number of precautionary restrictions on travel and events in response to the coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic.
Until further notice, public transport - including the metro and bus services - has been suspended around the country. Qatar has prohibited all social gatherings, postponed sporting and public events, and closed most public venues and shops, apart from supermarkets and pharmacies. Restaurants and cafes are either closed or only allowing take away orders. The authorities are deploying mobile patrols and setting up checkpoints to prevent social gatherings and anyone violating this may be detained. The authorities may also stop vehicles with more than one occupant to enquire about the reason for the journey.
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
You can find more information about cases in Qatar on the TravelHealthPro country page.
